[3] Brazil (Rio Grande do Norte)
Date: Fri 9 May 2008
Source: Globo [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/0,,MUL464281-9981,00-RN+DECRETA+EMERGENCIA+POR+CAUSA+DA+DENGUE.html>


The governor of Rio Grande do Norte declared a state of emergency due to
the large number of reported dengue cases. According to the report issued
by the state Secretariat of Public Health, there have been nearly 20 000
cases this year [2008].

The Secretariat of Health indicated that the disease has been recorded in
154 cities of Rio Grande do Norte state. Between 1 Jan and 3 May 2008, 19
157 cases have been reported. Of these, 78 cases have been DHF (the type of
dengue that is most serious). Examinations have revealed that 2 deaths were
caused by dengue.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[4] Indonesia (East Kalimantan)
Date: Mon 28 Apr 2008
Source: Tempo Interaktif [in Indonesian, machine translated, edited]
<http://www.tempointeraktif.com/hg/nusa/kalimantan/2008/04/28/brk,20080428-122110,id.html>


Dengue fever in East Kalimantan has killed 10 people each month in 2008. Up
to today [28 Apr 2008], dengue has caused 41 fatalities. The local
government up to now has not determined whether there was an extraordinary
incident in this case. "Mostly, patients died because they were handled too
late," said Parmono Kepala Sub Bidang Penanggulangan of Infectious Diseases
in the Health Service of East Kalimantan.

According to the data of the Health Service, during 2008 up until today [28
Apr 2008], 2396 dengue patients have been attended to. Of this number, 41
people died. Balikpapan city was recorded as the area having the most
dengue patients, with 865, 13 of whom died. This area was followed by
Samarinda in 2nd place, with 743 patients and 10 deaths, and the Kutai
Kartanegara region, with 231 patients and 8 deaths.

